` or make the counter an instance variable on `DocumentStore`.\n\n#### Important (Should Fix)\n\n**3. `findCommonAncestor` uses the fork-point snapshot by reference, not a deep clone**\n\n- **File**: `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 337-382\n- **What's wrong**: The method returns `source.forkPoint` or `target.forkPoint` directly (lines 343, 348, 369, 372). The returned `Map<string, DocumentState>` is then used in the `merge` method for reading (lines 163, 171), and importantly the `DocumentState` objects inside it are read via `.content` and `.deleted`. Since the fork point was created via `cloneDocuments` at branch creation time (line 120), it is a separate copy. However, if any code path were to mutate the returned map or its contents, the fork point itself would be corrupted for future merges.\n- **Why it matters**: Currently the merge code only reads from the base, so this is safe today. But it's fragile -- any future refactoring that accidentally mutates the base map would corrupt the fork-point data. A defensive clone when returning from `findCommonAncestor` would be safer.\n- **How to fix**: Return `this.cloneDocuments(forkPoint)` instead of returning the raw reference, or document that the return value must not be mutated.\n\n**4. `deepClone` does not handle `Date`, `RegExp`, `Map`, `Set`, or other special object types**\n\n- **File**: `/workspace/src/utils.ts`, lines 3-15\n- **What's wrong**: The `deepClone` function only handles plain objects and arrays. Any `Date`, `RegExp`, `Map`, `Set`, or class instance will be silently converted to a plain object with enumerable keys copied.\n- **Why it matters**: The spec says \"Documents are plain JSON objects,\" so this is technically within spec. However, `JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))` would handle `Date` (converting to string) more predictably, and `structuredClone` (available in Node.js 17+) would handle all of these correctly. If any caller accidentally passes a `Date` field, the current implementation would